{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17488367","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17488367"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T03:38:57+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T03:38:57+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"422"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"422","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/422"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.17,0.68,0.11,0.01,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"422"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103938"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"422","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/422"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"422"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86344"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"88"},{"type":"tags","id":"316"},{"type":"tags","id":"483"},{"type":"tags","id":"1087"},{"type":"tags","id":"1758"},{"type":"tags","id":"2283"},{"type":"tags","id":"2436"},{"type":"tags","id":"2589"},{"type":"tags","id":"2701"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4982"},{"type":"tags","id":"8118"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2431"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2446"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11354"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11364"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14803"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33519"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35724"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43008"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44754"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103938","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/103938"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 71-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a five-day history of productive cough with white-yellow coloured sputum. He denies any haemoptysis. He has also been experiencing increasing shortness of breath on exertion for the past four months. His medical history includes hypertension, type 2 diabetes mellitus (diet-controlled) and cataracts. His medications include amlodipine. He has a 25 pack-year smoking history but quit when he was 50 years old. He is a retired lawyer. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well. His pulse rate is 82/min, blood pressure 158/88 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 95% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. Auscultation of the chest reveals bilateral expiratory wheeze and diffuse inspiratory crackles. The remainder of the examination is normal.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate initial investigation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Lung function testing","Chest X-ray","High-resolution chest CT","CT chest with contrast","Arterial blood gas analysis"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis scenario presents a patient with respiratory symptoms suggestive of an acute exacerbation of COPD (which appears to be previously undiagnosed) or possibly pneumonia. A \u003Cstrong\u003Echest X-ray\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate initial investigation in this context. It can help identify pneumonia, rule out other causes of respiratory symptoms, and provide baseline information about the lungs that may suggest COPD. Given the patient\u0027s age, smoking history (though remote), and clinical presentation, COPD with an acute exacerbation is high on the differential diagnosis list, while the likelihood of lung cancer is relatively low, but this is still a diagnosis to consider.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELung function testing\u003C/strong\u003E is valuable for diagnosing and assessing the severity of COPD, but it is not the most appropriate initial test during an acute exacerbation. Spirometry should typically be performed when the patient is stable, not during an acute illness, as results may be temporarily worsened and not reflect baseline lung function. It would be more appropriate to perform lung function testing after the acute episode has resolved.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHigh-resolution chest CT\u003C/strong\u003E provides detailed images of lung parenchyma and is particularly useful for diagnosing interstitial lung diseases or bronchiectasis. However, it is not indicated as a first-line investigation for suspected COPD exacerbation or pneumonia. A CT chest should be considered if the chest X-ray is normal but symptoms persist unexplained, or if there are concerning findings on the chest X-ray that require further evaluation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECT chest with contrast\u003C/strong\u003E is typically used when there is suspicion of pulmonary embolism, mediastinal pathology, or to better characterize lung masses. While it provides excellent detail of both lung parenchyma and vasculature, it represents a significant radiation exposure and risks associated with contrast. It is not indicated as an initial investigation for suspected COPD exacerbation or pneumonia. It would be more appropriate after initial assessment with a chest X-ray if there were specific concerns requiring contrast enhancement.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EArterial blood gas analysis\u003C/strong\u003E is important in severe exacerbations of COPD to assess for respiratory failure and guide oxygen therapy. However, this patient appears clinically stable with oxygen saturation of 95% on room air, so arterial blood gas analysis is not necessary as the initial investigation. It would be more appropriate in patients with more severe symptoms or signs of respiratory distress.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Chest X-ray is the appropriate first-line investigation for suspected COPD exacerbation or pneumonia.","Clinical features of COPD exacerbation include increased dyspnoea, cough, and sputum production.","CT chest should be considered if chest X-ray is normal but symptoms persist or if there are concerning findings requiring further evaluation."],"references":["Stocks N. Lower respiratory tract infections and community acquired pneumonia in adults. Aust Fam Physician. 2004;33(5):297\u2013301.","Cancer Australia. Investigating symptoms of lung cancer a guide for all health professionals. May 2020. Accessed March 28 2024. https://www.canceraustralia.gov.au/cancer-types/lung-cancer/health-professionals/guidance-gps","McLellan R, Marshall H, Dent A, Bowman RV, Yang IA, Fong KM. Diagnosis and treatment of early lung cancer. AJGP [Internet]. 2020 August 8 [cited 2024 May 9];49(8). Available from:   https://doi.org/10.31128/ajgp-11-19-5148"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86344"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"422"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86344","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/86344"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-28T19:24:26+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-28T19:27:11+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"422"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103938"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"11","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec1","name":"Respiratory Medicine","synonyms":["Pulmonology"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"ta